The Virgin Islands needs viable and sustainable high-speed internet that can assist our farmers in irrigation, pesticide use, among other means for production. This is another opportunity to provide support for rural development and hardworking families.

Virgin Islanders are among many the many Americans struggling to meet their basic internet needs, ultimately limiting economic growth, educational advancements and medical developments. Leaving these Americans behind is inexcusable.

Fostering greater connectivity creates smart and environment friendly irrigation systems for farmers, additional software development jobs in rural areas, and educational opportunities for disadvantaged urban and rural children. #digitaldivde

Today, the Subcommittee on Commodity Exchange, Energy, and Credit in the House Agriculture Committee held a hearing, looking to analyze rural communities that have obtained and implemented broadband technology.

Currently, broadband is unavailable to roughly to 25 million Americans, 19 million of which live in rural areas, many of which with the highest levels of unemployment in the country. We must address the #digitaldivide!
